{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538413"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:27:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:27:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16171"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16171"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.2,0.5,0.23,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8862"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64202"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8862","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8862"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16171"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49634"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4266"},{"type":"tags","id":"4272"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21108"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30666"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64202"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after sustaining electrical burns from high-voltage power lines which collapsed during a bushfire. He has burns to his left forearm and both lower legs. He has a medical history of hypertension and asthma, for which he takes regular medications. He is a non-smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His vital signs are within normal limits. There are electrical burn marks across his left forearm and both lower legs. Initial resuscitation has commenced, and blood tests and X-rays of the affected limbs have been ordered. The burns unit has been notified.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most significant potential complication of this injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carbon monoxide poisoning","Soft tissue loss from liquefactive necrosis","Rhabdomyolysis","Soft tissue loss from coagulative necrosis","Peripheral neuropathy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHigh-voltage electrical burns are particularly dangerous because the extent of tissue damage is often much greater than what is visible on the surface. The path of electrical current through the body can cause extensive deep tissue injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERhabdomyolysis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most significant potential complication in this scenario. The electrical current causes massive destruction of muscle tissue, releasing myoglobin and other cellular contents into the circulation. This can lead to acute kidney injury, dangerous electrolyte imbalances, and compartment syndrome. Early recognition and aggressive fluid resuscitation are essential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarbon monoxide poisoning\u003C/strong\u003E, while a concern in fire-related injuries, is not typically associated with electrical burns. The patient\u0027s normal vital signs and examination make significant carbon monoxide exposure unlikely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESoft tissue loss from liquefactive necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly associated with bacterial infections rather than electrical burns. While tissue loss will occur, it is not the most immediate life-threatening complication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESoft tissue loss from coagulative necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E does occur in electrical burns but is a more localised process compared to the systemic effects of rhabdomyolysis. The tissue damage pattern in electrical burns typically shows coagulative necrosis at the entry and exit points.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeripheral neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E can occur following electrical burns but is usually a later complication and is not as immediately life-threatening as rhabdomyolysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement should focus on careful monitoring of renal function, creatine kinase levels, and urine output. Early recognition of compartment syndrome is crucial, and fasciotomy may be necessary if it develops.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["High-voltage electrical burns can cause extensive deep tissue damage that is not apparent on initial examination.","Rhabdomyolysis is a serious complication of electrical burns that can lead to acute kidney injury and compartment syndrome.","Early recognition and aggressive fluid resuscitation are essential in preventing complications of electrical burns."],"references":["Czuczman AD, Zane RD. Electrical injuries: a review for the emergency clinician. EB Medicine. 2009;11(10):1\u201324."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49634"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16171"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49634","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49634"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T07:52:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T07:53:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8862"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64202"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":nu